            <div1 type="letter">

<opener><dateline>225 Willard Way, Ithaca N.Y.<lb/>
Nov. 2, 1957</dateline>

<salute>Dear John:</salute></opener>

<p> The copies of the Missouri Alumnus came. Thank you so much. I really had not intended to bother you &amp;amp; supposed that my brother would go to the editorial office for them. One I sent to Rev. <unclear>Chuti</unclear> <del/> Another I shall deliver to Thompson. Both will <hi rend="underline">prize</hi> the copies. And then there is the third for me. You know how I shall value it, the pictures with all that they bring to mind of you and your home, family, &amp; horses, &amp; those wonderful extracts from your writing. How did they select so well?</p>

<p>And now I should tell you that your letter written in June &amp; addressed me at the Univ. of Washington was by some queer chance redirected here. So I only received it after coming back to Ithaca. That explains my neglect in replying. I am so glad it included that piece from the speech Journal. I rejoice in all the honors that came to you, who means

so very much to me.</p>

<p>I look out my window on fog &amp; haze, or rather a haze so dense as to be near fog. The hills are blotted out &amp; only close views are to be had. Such an attack is a typical harbinger of winter in this climate. But we have had a glorious fall. A gorgeous tapestry lay on the hills for some weeks. The maples, oaks, doogwood etc. were in full glow. I never cease to wonder at this brief visitation of unearthly beauty, perhaps it is nature's way of telling us that  though winter comes, all will be well, for spring awaits. There will be a resurrection of life.</p>

<p>You will be glad to know that we are well, though busy. I started to say "as usual" but then matters of <unclear/> has brought a piling up of things <del/> which we have not yet fully cleared away.</p>

<p>It was so nice to have had those good visits with you last summer, my dear friend. And I was so glad to have seen the girls &amp; Mrs. Neihardt, too.  May the spirited fire of you never dim  &amp; health continue to attend.</p>

<closer>Affectionately,
Slade </closer>

            </div1>
